♪ My name is Samuel ♪

394
00:32:04,631 --> 00:32:07,592
♪ Samuel ♪

395
00:32:07,759 --> 00:32:09,885
♪ My name is Samuel ♪

396
00:32:10,053 --> 00:32:12,888
♪ Samuel ♪

397
00:32:13,056 --> 00:32:14,974
♪ My name is Samuel ♪

398
00:32:15,142 --> 00:32:18,394
♪ And I'll see you all in hell ♪

399
00:32:18,562 --> 00:32:21,314
♪ I'll see you all in hell ♪

400
00:32:21,481 --> 00:32:23,357
♪ Damn your eyes. ♪

401
00:32:23,525 --> 00:32:27,612
(clanking)

402
00:32:34,953 --> 00:32:39,165
You're rich, right?
I mean your family.

403
00:32:39,333 --> 00:32:42,543
Well, I guess it depends on
whom you compare me to.

404
00:32:42,711 --> 00:32:46,172
Poor people.

405
00:32:46,340 --> 00:32:48,174
In that case, I reckon

406
00:32:48,342 --> 00:32:50,635
you could say
I grew up comfortably.

407
00:32:50,802 --> 00:32:55,181
Never rode with
a gentleman before.

408
00:32:55,349 --> 00:32:58,184
Never thought I would.

409
00:32:58,352 --> 00:33:00,770
(thunder rumbling)

410
00:33:00,937 --> 00:33:03,064
James's voice:
"Friendship is the most valuable thing

411
00:33:03,231 --> 00:33:05,066
a man can have.

412
00:33:05,233 --> 00:33:09,862
It's worth more than money,
land, horses or cattle.

413
00:33:10,030 --> 00:33:13,115
It might be the only thing
you never forget.

414
00:33:13,283 --> 00:33:15,201
And it lasts forever.

415
00:33:15,369 --> 00:33:18,746
Your father believed that.
Your mother did too."

416
00:33:35,389 --> 00:33:38,224
You just have to hold
the cards steady.

417
00:33:40,143 --> 00:33:42,770
Rattlesnake bites
are your thing,

418
00:33:42,938 --> 00:33:45,439
not mosquitoes.

419
00:33:47,150 --> 00:33:49,485
Etta bought these suits
so we could wear them, Butch.

420
00:33:49,653 --> 00:33:52,947
Now get up off your sorry ass
and come downstairs with us.

421
00:33:53,115 --> 00:33:56,325
Argentineans know plenty,
but not about poker...

422
00:33:56,493 --> 00:33:59,620
Not about poker,
my friend.

423
00:33:59,788 --> 00:34:01,664
You two are...

424
00:34:01,832 --> 00:34:04,667
you're quite a sight.

425
00:34:04,835 --> 00:34:08,129
All the more reason
for you to join us.

426
00:34:08,296 --> 00:34:10,798
Go on, get out of here,
damn it.

427
00:34:10,966 --> 00:34:12,675
I need some sleep.

428
00:34:12,843 --> 00:34:16,053
Bring me up something to drink.
And watch yourselves.

429
00:34:16,221 --> 00:34:20,141
Come on, Butch. Ain't nobody been
chasing us for a long time.

430
00:34:23,520 --> 00:34:25,354
"Ain't nobody been
chasing us

431
00:34:25,522 --> 00:34:28,482
for a long time."
Damn your eyes.

432
00:34:28,650 --> 00:34:31,402
Shut up. We'd have been
long gone three days ago

433
00:34:31,570 --> 00:34:34,238
if it hadn't been
for your mosquito bite.

434
00:34:34,406 --> 00:34:37,241
I can't even pronounce
the name of this damn place.

435
00:34:37,409 --> 00:34:40,286
San Juan.

436
00:34:40,454 --> 00:34:42,288
Anyways,

437
00:34:42,456 --> 00:34:44,498
and why the hell haven't
they put cuffs on us?

438
00:34:44,666 --> 00:34:47,877
They probably don't have
any handcuffs.

439
00:34:49,755 --> 00:34:51,672
This is humiliating.

440
00:34:51,840 --> 00:34:53,299
You don't say.

441
00:34:53,467 --> 00:34:55,551
(knocks on door)

442
00:34:59,973 --> 00:35:01,974
Oh, here we go.

443
00:35:03,268 --> 00:35:05,102
(speaks Spanish)
Sir.

444
00:35:05,270 --> 00:35:08,189
Here are your gringo bandits.
One's sick.

445
00:35:12,110 --> 00:35:14,361
Sorry to hear
you've not been too well.

446
00:35:14,529 --> 00:35:16,363
Oh, it's just an insect bite,

447
00:35:16,531 --> 00:35:18,324
Mr. Mackinley,
nothing serious.

448
00:35:18,492 --> 00:35:21,869
Yes, these places...
you never know

449
00:35:22,037 --> 00:35:25,206
what'll be the next
damn insect or vermin

450
00:35:25,373 --> 00:35:28,626
to rip a piece off of you.

451
00:35:28,794 --> 00:35:30,711
Look.

452
00:35:30,879 --> 00:35:34,298
Snakebite,
two years ago at Chaco.

453
00:35:34,466 --> 00:35:38,260
There's a saying around here:
"Dos pasitos"..."Two steps."

454
00:35:38,428 --> 00:35:41,263
They say by the third step
you're dead.

455
00:35:43,308 --> 00:35:46,685
I got lucky.

456
00:35:46,853 --> 00:35:49,522
This one

457
00:35:49,689 --> 00:35:53,108
was last winter in Atacama...

458
00:35:53,276 --> 00:35:55,277
a scorpion
the size of a clock.

459
00:35:55,445 --> 00:35:57,279
I could hardly walk
for two months.

460
00:35:57,447 --> 00:36:00,449
Then I was left
with this lump.

461
00:36:00,617 --> 00:36:03,244
But I'm sure
I'm not telling you

462
00:36:03,411 --> 00:36:05,955
a damn thing you don't
know yourselves.

463
00:36:06,122 --> 00:36:08,499
We've all been
in the same places.

464
00:36:08,667 --> 00:36:12,253
It was about time
we met face to face

465
00:36:12,420 --> 00:36:13,879
finally.

466
00:36:14,047 --> 00:36:17,508
Go to hell, Mackinley.
Let's get it over with.

467
00:36:17,676 --> 00:36:19,802
- I can't wait.
- (knocks on door)

468
00:36:19,970 --> 00:36:22,930
(speaks Spanish)
Open. It's the sheriff.

469
00:36:28,270 --> 00:36:30,312
Sundance:
Mr. Albion Mackinley,

470
00:36:30,480 --> 00:36:32,898
May I introduce
Miss Etta Place?

471
00:36:36,152 --> 00:36:39,196
Well well, Mackinley.

472
00:36:39,364 --> 00:36:41,073
My, you're a gentleman.

473
00:36:41,241 --> 00:36:43,409
I thought all Pinkerton men

474
00:36:43,577 --> 00:36:46,412
were bloodthirsty thugs

475
00:36:46,580 --> 00:36:48,664
sold to the highest bidder.

476
00:36:48,832 --> 00:36:50,791
You gonna run
in your underwear?

477
00:36:50,959 --> 00:36:52,751
What?

478
00:36:52,919 --> 00:36:54,670
(laughing)

479
00:36:58,383 --> 00:37:00,718
(speaking Quechua)

480
00:37:04,848 --> 00:37:06,557
(both laughing)

481
00:37:09,102 --> 00:37:13,647
(speaking Spanish)
I have a gift for you.

482
00:37:20,030 --> 00:37:22,489
It's a gringo machine.

483
00:37:22,657 --> 00:37:24,575
Silver is best used
for other things.

484
00:37:24,743 --> 00:37:26,243
I don't understand that time.

485
00:37:26,411 --> 00:37:28,412
Yeah, me neither.

486
00:37:29,581 --> 00:37:31,373
Don't do that! It's mine!

487
00:37:36,504 --> 00:37:38,339
Keep it.

488
00:37:38,506 --> 00:37:40,716
It's something
to remember me by.

489
00:37:41,843 --> 00:37:45,262
Cheers.

490
00:37:45,430 --> 00:37:47,056
To the two of you.

491
00:37:50,685 --> 00:37:53,145
I'm going to go.
It's dark out.

492
00:37:55,523 --> 00:37:56,899
Yana,

493
00:37:58,234 --> 00:38:02,112
you know I'm going back
to my country tomorrow.

494
00:38:02,280 --> 00:38:03,697
For good.

495
00:38:03,865 --> 00:38:06,325
Spend the night here, please.

496
00:38:08,078 --> 00:38:09,078
I can't.

497
00:38:10,080 --> 00:38:13,540
My family's waiting for me.
It's dark out.

498
00:38:15,585 --> 00:38:16,669
Sure.

499
00:38:24,386 --> 00:38:26,595
I have rain gear.

500
00:38:29,349 --> 00:38:31,141
- No?
- No.

501
00:38:42,153 --> 00:38:45,280
Goodbye, Mr. James.
Take care of yourself.

502
00:39:10,724 --> 00:39:12,808
What about all this?

503
00:39:14,310 --> 00:39:15,519
This?

504
00:39:15,687 --> 00:39:18,939
Eh, it's just a place.

505
00:39:19,107 --> 00:39:21,817
Yana and her family
will make good use of it.

506
00:39:21,985 --> 00:39:24,278
They live off the land.

507
00:39:26,531 --> 00:39:27,698
More?

508
00:39:37,167 --> 00:39:40,794
About two months ago
I got a letter from San Francisco.

509
00:39:40,962 --> 00:39:45,466
A woman I'd loved very much

510
00:39:45,633 --> 00:39:48,635
died of tuberculosis,

511
00:39:48,803 --> 00:39:50,637
left an only kid...

512
00:39:50,805 --> 00:39:54,349
a son I've never
seen before.

513
00:39:56,853 --> 00:39:59,438
So I figured...

514
00:40:02,776 --> 00:40:05,110
now might be a good time
to go back

515
00:40:05,278 --> 00:40:07,112
and pay him a visit, you know,

516
00:40:07,280 --> 00:40:10,240
keep each other company.

517
00:40:10,408 --> 00:40:12,242
Sometimes I think

518
00:40:12,410 --> 00:40:15,329
there's only two moments
in a man's life:

519
00:40:15,497 --> 00:40:17,331
One's when he leaves home;
and the other one's

520
00:40:17,499 --> 00:40:19,583
when he returns.

521
00:40:19,751 --> 00:40:23,879
Everything else is just
in the middle.

522
00:40:24,047 --> 00:40:25,881
Well, looks like
we'll be headed

523
00:40:26,049 --> 00:40:28,634
in different
directions, ain't we?

524
00:40:31,721 --> 00:40:34,098
- (footsteps)
- (horse tack jingling)

525
00:41:06,923 --> 00:41:08,257
Mr. James?

526
00:41:09,968 --> 00:41:11,593
Yana?

527
00:41:16,182 --> 00:41:18,851
(horse neighs)

528
00:41:24,315 --> 00:41:26,650
(snoring)

529
00:41:52,051 --> 00:41:53,552
Good morning.

530
00:41:55,096 --> 00:41:56,805
What do you want?

531
00:41:56,973 --> 00:41:59,683
We found your horse
in the desert four days ago.

532
00:42:01,853 --> 00:42:03,645
Where is he?

533
00:42:03,813 --> 00:42:04,813
He's dead.

534
00:42:04,981 --> 00:42:07,649
But we have your blankets
and your money.

535
00:42:10,528 --> 00:42:11,820
James:
So?

536
00:42:13,072 --> 00:42:15,199
Where's your friend
the Spaniard?

537
00:42:21,664 --> 00:42:22,873
What friend?

538
00:42:23,041 --> 00:42:24,124
- Fucking gringo!
- (gunshot)

539
00:42:24,292 --> 00:42:25,792
(horse neighs)

540
00:42:32,300 --> 00:42:34,426
(Yana panting)

541
00:42:39,474 --> 00:42:41,475
(gun clicks)

542
00:43:01,037 --> 00:43:03,121
(panting)

543
00:43:17,470 --> 00:43:20,472
(gunshots)

544
00:43:43,246 --> 00:44:00,679
Yana.

545
00:44:57,695 --> 00:45:00,197
(James groaning)

546
00:45:13,294 --> 00:45:15,087
Yana!

547
00:45:33,898 --> 00:45:36,274
That's enough.

548
00:45:42,657 --> 00:45:44,950
All right, let's get
this over with.

549
00:45:45,118 --> 00:45:46,743
Go.

550
00:45:48,204 --> 00:45:51,164
Argh!

551
00:45:51,332 --> 00:45:53,333
Shit!

552
00:46:01,843 --> 00:46:04,010
Here, you might need
to use this.

553
00:46:32,707 --> 00:46:34,958
Thanks for that.

554
00:46:45,052 --> 00:46:46,887
They're smart.

555
00:46:47,054 --> 00:46:49,681
Someone must have told them
we were together,

556
00:46:49,849 --> 00:46:53,143
so they sent two women
so we wouldn't suspect.

557
00:46:53,311 --> 00:46:55,353
When they realize
they are not coming back,

558
00:46:55,521 --> 00:46:57,606
they will come after us.

559
00:47:04,572 --> 00:47:06,156
(speaking Aymara)

560
00:47:34,560 --> 00:47:36,561
(train horn blowing)

561
00:47:36,729 --> 00:47:39,356
(crossing bells dinging)

562
00:47:55,581 --> 00:47:57,707
Is he waiting outside?

563
00:47:57,875 --> 00:48:00,126
Yeah.

564
00:48:00,294 --> 00:48:03,713
It's a long trip.

565
00:48:03,881 --> 00:48:06,383
If I made it here,
I can make it back.

566
00:48:09,720 --> 00:48:12,305
We all can.

567
00:48:14,767 --> 00:48:16,768
He'll forgive you.

568
00:48:16,936 --> 00:48:18,770
You know what he's like.

569
00:48:18,938 --> 00:48:22,941
Nothing to forgive, Butch.
I'm not walking out on you.

570
00:48:23,109 --> 00:48:25,819
I'm just defending
what's ours.

571
00:48:25,987 --> 00:48:28,029
Conductor:
ISale a Oruro!

572
00:48:28,197 --> 00:48:30,198
(horn blows)

573
00:48:31,993 --> 00:48:33,827
Conductor:
Pasajeros con destino a Oruro

574
00:48:33,995 --> 00:48:35,662
a abordar el tren.

575
00:48:35,830 --> 00:48:39,291
ISale a Oruro!

576
00:48:39,458 --> 00:48:42,043
Come with me.

577
00:48:42,211 --> 00:48:43,837
Come on.

578
00:48:44,005 --> 00:48:46,047
You're not young anymore.

579
00:48:47,717 --> 00:48:50,677
Truth be told,
we're still losing, Butch.

580
00:48:50,845 --> 00:48:53,805
You'd never have any peace.

581
00:48:53,973 --> 00:48:55,307
(train horn blows)

582
00:48:59,687 --> 00:49:01,521
Conductor:
IUltimo llamado!

583
00:49:01,689 --> 00:49:03,148
(bell dinging)

584
00:49:03,316 --> 00:49:05,525
I love you both.

585
00:49:07,862 --> 00:49:09,529
Tell him.

586
00:49:14,035 --> 00:49:17,579
Wait, what will you name it?

587
00:49:17,747 --> 00:49:19,372
Ryan.

588
00:49:41,062 --> 00:49:43,021
She'll come back.

589
00:49:43,189 --> 00:49:45,106
I know it.

590
00:49:45,274 --> 00:49:48,568
Of course.

591
00:49:48,736 --> 00:49:51,071
Who could stay away
from all this?

592
00:49:55,242 --> 00:49:58,328
♪ If the world from you withholds ♪

593
00:49:58,496 --> 00:50:01,831
♪ All its silver and its gold ♪

594
00:50:01,999 --> 00:50:04,125
♪ And you have to get along ♪

595
00:50:04,293 --> 00:50:06,753
♪ With meager fare ♪

596
00:50:06,921 --> 00:50:10,507
♪ Just remember in God's world ♪

597
00:50:10,675 --> 00:50:13,968
♪ How he fed them little birds ♪

598
00:50:14,136 --> 00:50:16,638
♪ Take your burden
to the Lord ♪

599
00:50:16,806 --> 00:50:19,224
♪ And leave it there ♪

600
00:50:19,392 --> 00:50:22,644
♪ Leave it there ♪

601
00:50:22,812 --> 00:50:25,980
♪ Oh, leave it there ♪

602
00:50:26,148 --> 00:50:29,067
♪ Take your burden
to the Lord ♪

603
00:50:29,235 --> 00:50:31,486
♪ And leave it there. ♪

604
00:50:33,531 --> 00:50:36,408
The Uyuni Salt Flats.

605
00:50:38,202 --> 00:50:40,620
There's nothing
more beautiful,

606
00:50:40,788 --> 00:50:43,623
like a sweet death.

607
00:50:43,791 --> 00:50:45,625
It'll be tough,

608
00:50:45,793 --> 00:50:48,253
but it's the only way
across those mountains.

609
00:50:48,421 --> 00:50:50,255
The other side...
I can catch me

610
00:50:50,423 --> 00:50:53,383
a boat back home
from Chile or Peru.

611
00:50:58,472 --> 00:50:59,931
(chuckles)

612
00:51:00,099 --> 00:51:03,017
Come on over here, son.

613
00:51:04,937 --> 00:51:06,563
Get down.

614
00:51:10,526 --> 00:51:12,610
Drop your pants.

615
00:51:12,778 --> 00:51:14,237
Are you nuts?

616
00:51:14,405 --> 00:51:16,573
If we don't heal
those saddle wounds,

617
00:51:16,741 --> 00:51:19,242
you can't ride.
You're gonna die out here.

618
00:51:19,410 --> 00:51:21,578
Come on, turn around.

619
00:51:25,583 --> 00:51:28,209
You ready?

620
00:51:28,377 --> 00:51:30,587
This might sting a little bit.

621
00:51:30,755 --> 00:51:33,006
Oy.

622
00:51:33,174 --> 00:51:35,675
(grunting)

623
00:51:38,220 --> 00:51:39,387
Argh!

624
00:51:39,555 --> 00:51:41,014
There you go.

625
00:51:41,182 --> 00:51:43,600
- Fuck!
- (chuckles)

626
00:51:45,853 --> 00:51:49,314
Your ass is softer
than a bookkeeper's.

627
00:51:49,482 --> 00:51:51,483
You okay?

628
00:51:51,650 --> 00:51:54,110
Yeah.

629
00:51:57,740 --> 00:52:00,867
James: It's been a long time
since I've been out here.

630
00:52:03,245 --> 00:52:05,538
I like these places.

631
00:52:05,706 --> 00:52:07,874
They can't be used.

632
00:52:08,042 --> 00:52:09,292
They got no owners.

633
00:52:09,460 --> 00:52:12,212
But they will.
That's how life works.

634
00:52:12,379 --> 00:52:14,881
Well, I hope I'm dead
when that day comes.

635
00:52:17,301 --> 00:52:21,805
James, I wanted to say,

636
00:52:21,972 --> 00:52:24,349
all that happened
about Yana and...

637
00:52:24,517 --> 00:52:26,392
Nah.

638
00:52:26,560 --> 00:52:29,687
Look, I knew the risks
as well as you, going in.

639
00:52:29,855 --> 00:52:32,357
There's nothing to say.

640
00:52:35,736 --> 00:52:37,654
We should shelter up
down there.

641
00:52:37,822 --> 00:52:40,406
It's gonna freeze tonight.

642
00:52:40,574 --> 00:52:43,284
James:
These horses ain't gonna last very long

643
00:52:43,452 --> 00:52:46,871
at this altitude...
no air, no water.

644
00:52:48,749 --> 00:52:52,335
Eduardo:
What did you do in your country?

645
00:52:52,503 --> 00:52:54,337
(James chuckles)

646
00:52:54,505 --> 00:52:58,424
I think you got a pretty
good idea, don't you?

647
00:52:58,592 --> 00:53:01,386
(Eduardo chuckles)

648
00:53:03,389 --> 00:53:06,432
James:
We covered more than six states

649
00:53:06,600 --> 00:53:10,645
back in the day,

650
00:53:10,813 --> 00:53:15,567
some of 'em bigger
than this whole country.

651
00:53:15,734 --> 00:53:18,152
Of course things were
different back then.

652
00:53:18,320 --> 00:53:22,031
There was room
for everybody.

653
00:53:22,199 --> 00:53:26,494
Then the railroad came in
and the big ranchers

654
00:53:26,662 --> 00:53:30,415
and everything changed.

655
00:53:30,583 --> 00:53:34,335
It turned into a kind of a war.

656
00:53:34,503 --> 00:53:38,673
We ended up on the losing end
of the stick.

657
00:53:38,841 --> 00:53:40,300
And why Bolivia?

658
00:53:40,467 --> 00:53:44,387
It was far far away.

659
00:53:44,555 --> 00:53:46,306
Far away from what?

660
00:53:46,473 --> 00:53:48,266
Everything.

661
00:53:48,434 --> 00:53:51,728
See, one day

662
00:53:51,896 --> 00:53:55,148
I woke up

663
00:53:55,316 --> 00:53:57,066
and found myself alone.

664
00:53:57,234 --> 00:53:59,152
Seemed like everybody I knew

665
00:53:59,320 --> 00:54:01,821
was either dead or in jail.

666
00:54:01,989 --> 00:54:03,990
They thought I was dead too.

667
00:54:04,158 --> 00:54:05,617
So I just did

668
00:54:05,784 --> 00:54:07,619
what any good
dead person would do.

669
00:54:07,786 --> 00:54:10,872
I went off and raised me
some horses.

670
00:54:11,040 --> 00:54:13,249
20 years...

671
00:54:13,417 --> 00:54:15,793
that was a big change.

672
00:54:15,961 --> 00:54:18,671
Quiet times.

673
00:54:18,839 --> 00:54:21,841
You see, I'm too long
in the tooth

674
00:54:22,009 --> 00:54:23,843
to go off and be what
I used to be, you know...

675
00:54:24,011 --> 00:54:26,137
just an ordinary
old bandit.

676
00:54:26,305 --> 00:54:29,641
You should have become
a rancher too.

677
00:54:29,808 --> 00:54:33,728
You'd be rich now,
instead of being here with me.

678
00:54:33,896 --> 00:54:36,522
Rich?

679
00:54:36,690 --> 00:54:39,525
I've been my own man.

680
00:54:39,693 --> 00:54:43,279
Ain't nothing richer than that.

681
00:54:43,447 --> 00:54:45,448
Had some good friends too.

682
00:54:53,707 --> 00:54:55,583
They don't sleep.

683
00:54:57,544 --> 00:55:01,005
Sure you killed a few not-so-friendly
in those days, huh?

684
00:55:01,173 --> 00:55:03,758
Me? I've never
had to kill nobody.

685
00:55:03,926 --> 00:55:06,469
So far.

686
00:55:06,637 --> 00:55:08,638
Come on, let's get these
horses saddled up.

687
00:55:20,401 --> 00:55:22,652
(speaking Aymara)

688
00:55:33,539 --> 00:55:35,957
James:
They must be very well paid.

689
00:55:36,125 --> 00:55:39,961
I've never seen anybody
take so much punishment.

690
00:55:40,129 --> 00:55:42,588
Eduardo: We should have never tried
to cross the salt flats.

691
00:55:42,756 --> 00:55:45,341
James: It's the only way.
Otherwise they'd have surrounded us

692
00:55:45,509 --> 00:55:47,343
and we wouldn't even
see it coming.

693
00:55:47,511 --> 00:55:50,138
This way all they can do
is track us

694
00:55:50,305 --> 00:55:53,349
and see whose horses
die first.

695
00:56:12,619 --> 00:56:14,746
(horse huffing)

696
00:56:14,913 --> 00:56:16,414
Vamos.

697
00:56:16,582 --> 00:56:19,208
(grunts)

698
00:56:23,255 --> 00:56:26,215
(horse huffing)

699
00:56:28,719 --> 00:56:31,429
Grab the rifle and the water
and come on.

700
00:56:31,597 --> 00:56:33,890
Mount up.

701
00:56:36,351 --> 00:56:39,854
- (gunshot)
- (horses neigh)

702
00:56:40,022 --> 00:56:42,065
Come on, let's go.

703
00:57:07,549 --> 00:57:09,967
(yelling in Aymara)

704
00:57:25,275 --> 00:57:27,235
Three men on horseback.

705
00:57:27,402 --> 00:57:30,196
We still have a few minutes.

706
00:57:32,157 --> 00:57:34,200
We stand a chance here, right?

707
00:57:34,368 --> 00:57:36,911
I don't know.

708
00:57:39,039 --> 00:57:40,790
James,

709
00:57:40,958 --> 00:57:42,917
I'm glad I'm with you.

710
00:57:43,085 --> 00:57:46,671
You know, before I met you...
damn the day...

711
00:57:46,839 --> 00:57:49,132
I thought if I was gonna
die of old age,

712
00:57:49,299 --> 00:57:51,134
I might as well
go back home to do it.

713
00:57:51,301 --> 00:57:54,971
But, hell, this seems like
as good a day as any to die.

714
00:57:55,139 --> 00:57:57,682
We are not gonna die, old man.

715
00:57:57,850 --> 00:58:00,434
Of course not, son.
Nobody ever does.

716
00:58:00,602 --> 00:58:02,603
Just in case, we ought
to bury this money

717
00:58:02,771 --> 00:58:05,189
before Patiño gets
his hands on it again.

718
00:58:05,357 --> 00:58:08,234
Too late.
They are too close.

719
00:58:14,491 --> 00:58:17,910
They're gonna surround us.
They know we're here.

720
00:58:28,422 --> 00:58:31,174
(whispers)
Dios mio.

721
00:58:37,431 --> 00:58:39,891
What are we gonna do?

722
00:58:56,241 --> 00:58:57,867
(cocks rifle)

723
00:59:04,208 --> 00:59:06,709
All right, look.

724
00:59:06,877 --> 00:59:09,212
You take the good horse
and the money.

725
00:59:09,379 --> 00:59:11,964
Head southeast.
You follow that mountain range.

726
00:59:12,132 --> 00:59:14,884
- If you're lucky, you'll wind up in Tupiza.
- What?

727
00:59:15,052 --> 00:59:17,053
I'm gonna take the other horse
and head southwest.

728
00:59:17,221 --> 00:59:19,931
Their horses have to be wiped out by now.
I'll meet you down there.

729
00:59:20,098 --> 00:59:22,225
- But...
- It's the only way to do it... splitting up.

730
00:59:22,392 --> 00:59:26,270
- They'll kill us.
- This desert will kill you before they do.

731
00:59:26,438 --> 00:59:28,606
I don't want to be
by myself.

732
00:59:28,774 --> 00:59:31,359
Your horse will make it,
don't worry.

733
00:59:34,321 --> 00:59:37,865
All right, just remember...
southeast, okay?

734
00:59:38,033 --> 00:59:40,701
And don't buy one of those goddamn
mansions full of flowers, all right?

735
00:59:40,869 --> 00:59:43,037
- You spend that money quick.
- But...

736
00:59:43,205 --> 00:59:45,122
(whistles) Hiya!

737
00:59:45,290 --> 00:59:46,624
Shit!

738
00:59:56,385 --> 00:59:58,261
(whistles)

739
01:00:07,521 --> 01:00:09,772
Yahoo!

740
01:00:09,940 --> 01:00:13,693
Yahoo! Yah!

741
01:00:13,860 --> 01:00:15,861
Yah!

742
01:00:20,701 --> 01:00:23,869
- (gunshot)
- (horse neighs)

743
01:00:24,037 --> 01:00:27,623
(grunts)

744
01:00:59,156 --> 01:01:01,365
(grunting)

745
01:01:02,868 --> 01:01:04,201
(speaking Spanish)
Don't move.

746
01:01:06,830 --> 01:01:08,622
Don't move!

747
01:01:19,634 --> 01:01:22,136
Drop the gun,
you son of a bitch.

748
01:01:38,111 --> 01:01:40,154
(panting)

749
01:02:08,558 --> 01:02:10,643
(gun clicks)

750
01:02:12,771 --> 01:02:14,897
(clicks)

751
01:03:06,533 --> 01:03:08,701
(speaking Spanish)
How many times did we go out

752
01:03:09,703 --> 01:03:12,496
hunting together, my friend?

753
01:03:12,664 --> 01:03:14,248
(cocks gun)

754
01:03:16,251 --> 01:03:17,251
Fucking Spaniard!

755
01:03:17,419 --> 01:03:19,545
(gunshot)

756
01:05:10,323 --> 01:05:12,366
(horse huffing)

757
01:05:30,760 --> 01:05:33,012
(gunfire)

758
01:05:46,693 --> 01:05:48,944
Whoa.
Get on, Sundance.

759
01:05:53,617 --> 01:05:56,118
Ain't nobody following us.

760
01:05:56,286 --> 01:05:58,454
They think we're back
at the corral.

761
01:05:58,622 --> 01:06:01,123
The bullet's still inside.

762
01:06:03,251 --> 01:06:05,794
You think the Chilean and the Yankee
will make it?

763
01:06:05,962 --> 01:06:08,130
When they find their bodies,
they'll think they're us.

764
01:06:08,298 --> 01:06:10,299
Then we're free.

765
01:06:10,467 --> 01:06:13,344
I like being dead.

766
01:06:13,511 --> 01:06:15,220
Hell, if I'd only known sooner.

767
01:06:15,388 --> 01:06:17,681
Give me your hand, Sundance.

768
01:06:17,849 --> 01:06:20,809
I should've gone with Etta

769
01:06:20,977 --> 01:06:23,270
and the boy.

770
01:06:23,438 --> 01:06:27,441
A son... that's more than a lot of people
have to say for themselves.

771
01:06:27,609 --> 01:06:31,320
Don't you think?

772
01:06:31,488 --> 01:06:34,198
What makes you think
he's yours, you desert dog?

773
01:06:34,366 --> 01:06:37,826
Oh, it doesn't matter.
He'll still be my son.

774
01:06:37,994 --> 01:06:41,205
Let's head for
the mountains, Butch.

775
01:06:41,373 --> 01:06:43,957
We'll cross those mountains
and go home.

776
01:06:45,752 --> 01:06:48,212
Damn Bolivian army...

777
01:06:48,380 --> 01:06:50,714
worst aim I've ever seen.

778
01:07:12,737 --> 01:07:15,197
(pounding on door)

779
01:07:22,080 --> 01:07:24,707
(speaking Spanish)
Goddamn little doctor!

780
01:07:24,874 --> 01:07:27,167
I told you, I'll pay you.

781
01:07:27,335 --> 01:07:28,961
I was just fine in the bar!

782
01:07:29,129 --> 01:07:31,255
That's not why I called for you.

783
01:07:31,423 --> 01:07:33,632
Mr. Mackinley,
come in, come in.

784
01:07:38,596 --> 01:07:41,306
When you worked
for the Pinkertons,

785
01:07:41,474 --> 01:07:45,436
you came here to Bolivia
chasing bandits, right?

786
01:07:45,603 --> 01:07:47,438
Well, that's excellent!

787
01:07:47,605 --> 01:07:49,523
I found my memory!

788
01:07:49,691 --> 01:07:53,694
And it turns out it's
a goddamn Bolivian quack.

789
01:07:55,196 --> 01:07:57,990
If I remember right,
you always said

790
01:07:58,158 --> 01:08:02,161
the men they killed in San Vicente
weren't your bandits.

791
01:08:03,163 --> 01:08:06,665
Well, you might have been right.

792
01:08:08,626 --> 01:08:09,918
But...

793
01:08:10,086 --> 01:08:12,755
you're not too drunk, are you?

794
01:08:12,922 --> 01:08:14,381
Fuck off.

795
01:08:14,549 --> 01:08:16,133
Well,

796
01:08:16,301 --> 01:08:20,095
now we're going to see
if you were right or not.

797
01:08:21,347 --> 01:08:22,431
Look.

798
01:08:44,162 --> 01:08:46,663
Sweet Jesus.

799
01:08:48,166 --> 01:08:51,627
Sweet suffering Jesus,
it's him.

800
01:08:51,795 --> 01:08:53,754
It's him, isn't it?

801
01:08:53,922 --> 01:08:55,672
Yes.

802
01:08:55,840 --> 01:08:58,008
Robert Leroy Parker.

803
01:08:59,052 --> 01:09:00,385
Butch Cassidy.

804
01:09:00,553 --> 01:09:03,555
All of them will apologize to me.

805
01:09:04,849 --> 01:09:06,600
All those bastards.

806
01:09:07,602 --> 01:09:09,353
What's he got?

807
01:09:09,521 --> 01:09:11,063
A bullet wound,

808
01:09:11,231 --> 01:09:14,358
dehydration and fatigue.

809
01:09:15,401 --> 01:09:17,152
He just needs to rest.

810
01:09:20,490 --> 01:09:22,366
Rest...

811
01:09:35,964 --> 01:09:38,632
(distant rooster crows)

812
01:10:02,657 --> 01:10:04,825
Here we are.

813
01:10:12,208 --> 01:10:14,209
You and me.

814
01:10:16,212 --> 01:10:18,630
(coughing)

815
01:10:29,893 --> 01:10:31,143
Water!

816
01:10:40,987 --> 01:10:43,530
You're in poor shape,

817
01:10:43,698 --> 01:10:45,532
even worse
than the last time

818
01:10:45,700 --> 01:10:47,743
we saw each other.

819
01:10:49,454 --> 01:10:52,623
What the fuck are you
doing in Bolivia?

820
01:10:52,790 --> 01:10:55,542
Haven't you got
anything better to do?

821
01:10:55,710 --> 01:10:57,377
And where's my pistol?

822
01:11:01,799 --> 01:11:04,009
What should I call you?

823
01:11:05,970 --> 01:11:09,181
I've been going under Blackthorn.
Doesn't matter.

824
01:11:09,349 --> 01:11:13,518
It matters.
Of course it does.

825
01:11:17,023 --> 01:11:19,816
I never believed
you were dead, you know.

826
01:11:26,866 --> 01:11:29,576
Strange world,

827
01:11:29,744 --> 01:11:33,664
wouldn't you agree,
Mr. Blackthorn?

828
01:11:51,140 --> 01:11:54,309
I'm what they call
an honorary consul...

829
01:11:54,477 --> 01:11:56,603
$89 a month,

830
01:11:56,771 --> 01:11:58,605
a one-bedroom house

831
01:11:58,773 --> 01:12:01,817
with a bed too small
for my tastes.

832
01:12:01,985 --> 01:12:05,362
I just greet the few
North Americans

833
01:12:05,530 --> 01:12:07,614
that show up around here...

834
01:12:07,782 --> 01:12:10,158
gold diggers,
people buying wool,

835
01:12:10,326 --> 01:12:11,994
drunkards,
an occasional runaway...

836
01:12:12,161 --> 01:12:15,455
not many people.

837
01:12:15,623 --> 01:12:20,085
The last one came by

838
01:12:20,253 --> 01:12:23,213
two winters past.

839
01:12:23,381 --> 01:12:26,717
I spend the rest of time
looking out the window.

840
01:12:26,884 --> 01:12:30,971
Huh, sad story.
Not much of a life.

841
01:12:31,139 --> 01:12:32,973
No. No, it's not.

842
01:12:33,141 --> 01:12:35,684
But I couldn't aspire
to much more...

843
01:12:38,187 --> 01:12:40,355
until today.

844
01:12:40,523 --> 01:12:43,150
Last night I thought

845
01:12:43,317 --> 01:12:46,028
everything could
change for me.

846
01:12:46,195 --> 01:12:49,656
I could even buy a huge bed

847
01:12:49,824 --> 01:12:53,952
and travel home on it,
smiling and waving

848
01:12:54,120 --> 01:12:57,372
as I passed.

849
01:12:59,625 --> 01:13:03,378
But, Mr. Blackthorn,

850
01:13:03,546 --> 01:13:07,799
these past few hours
at your side

851
01:13:07,967 --> 01:13:10,927
have reminded me
of many things...

852
01:13:11,095 --> 01:13:12,929
the fatigue,

853
01:13:13,097 --> 01:13:17,893
the years of pursuit.

854
01:13:18,061 --> 01:13:22,189
Carrying out one's duty is,

855
01:13:22,356 --> 01:13:25,067
believe me,

856
01:13:25,234 --> 01:13:29,029
exhausting.

857
01:13:29,197 --> 01:13:33,992
Here in this
godforsaken village

858
01:13:34,160 --> 01:13:37,370
I finally found some rest...

859
01:13:37,538 --> 01:13:39,581
a stupid

860
01:13:39,749 --> 01:13:42,292
but well-deserved rest.

861
01:13:42,460 --> 01:13:46,171
Well,

862
01:13:46,339 --> 01:13:49,299
I guess we can't be blamed
for growing older.

863
01:13:49,467 --> 01:13:51,635
We're too old
to keep on playing.

864
01:13:51,803 --> 01:13:54,971
Never was a game with me.

865
01:13:55,139 --> 01:13:57,474
Of course it was...

866
01:13:57,642 --> 01:14:00,393
an absurd, deadly game.

867
01:14:00,561 --> 01:14:03,480
Eh, you never understood.
Doesn't matter.

868
01:14:03,648 --> 01:14:06,691
Of course I understood.
I was part of the game.

869
01:14:06,859 --> 01:14:08,819
But this time...

870
01:14:08,986 --> 01:14:11,071
There's no handcuffs either.

871
01:14:11,239 --> 01:14:14,366
This time you're on your own.

872
01:14:14,534 --> 01:14:17,160
No one will come
to the rescue.

873
01:14:17,328 --> 01:14:19,746
Do whatever
you need to do.

874
01:14:37,098 --> 01:14:39,307
Take it.

875
01:14:39,475 --> 01:14:44,563
Consider it a way
to continue resting.

876
01:14:52,738 --> 01:14:56,324
An army battalion
is on its way here.

877
01:14:56,492 --> 01:14:58,326
I sent for them.

878
01:14:58,494 --> 01:15:00,871
This is the most important thing to have
happened around here

879
01:15:01,038 --> 01:15:03,790
since... well,
since your death.

880
01:15:03,958 --> 01:15:05,208
(chuckles)

881
01:15:05,376 --> 01:15:09,171
I'll get you to a safe place.

882
01:15:09,338 --> 01:15:11,298
You'll leave

883
01:15:11,465 --> 01:15:14,759
and you'll never come back.

884
01:15:14,927 --> 01:15:18,763
Things will still be the same.

885
01:15:22,310 --> 01:15:25,395
You're a right pain
in the ass, Cassidy...

886
01:15:25,563 --> 01:15:29,900
a right fucking
pain in the ass.

887
01:15:33,571 --> 01:15:35,030
(speaking Spanish)
We're here.

888
01:15:46,250 --> 01:15:47,918
There's food and chicha in here.

889
01:15:48,085 --> 01:15:49,127
Thanks.

890
01:15:52,715 --> 01:15:54,341
I know what you are, sir.

891
01:15:55,801 --> 01:15:57,928
Please, don't steal from me.

892
01:16:02,308 --> 01:16:04,267
Iván...

893
01:16:04,435 --> 01:16:06,728
you won't say anything,
will you?

894
01:16:06,896 --> 01:16:10,023
No, sir. You're my guest.

895
01:16:36,467 --> 01:16:39,344
(church bells ringing)

896
01:17:31,272 --> 01:17:34,607
James's voice:
"Dear Ryan, I have enough money now

897
01:17:34,775 --> 01:17:36,943
for us to start
a brand-new life...

898
01:17:37,111 --> 01:17:39,487
maybe horses, ranching.

899
01:17:39,655 --> 01:17:42,532
I've met an old friend
of your father and mother's.

900
01:17:42,700 --> 01:17:45,285
He remembers them often.
They were one of a kind.

901
01:17:45,453 --> 01:17:48,163
There's not much blood
like yours left.

902
01:17:48,331 --> 01:17:51,041
I'm on my way back.

903
01:17:51,208 --> 01:17:53,543
I don't know how long it will take...
not more than two months.

904
01:17:53,711 --> 01:17:57,047
With love,
your Uncle Butch."

905
01:17:59,633 --> 01:18:02,635
Hey, I was just
writing about you.

906
01:18:02,803 --> 01:18:05,055
I should have left you
in the damn clinic.

907
01:18:05,222 --> 01:18:09,684
Eduardo Apodaca
is a friend of yours?

908
01:18:09,852 --> 01:18:11,686
Have you seen him?
Where is he?

909
01:18:11,854 --> 01:18:14,439
He's heading west through the canyons.
He was in Tupiza,

910
01:18:14,607 --> 01:18:16,983
but made himself scarce
when he saw the uproar

911
01:18:17,151 --> 01:18:18,985
caused by your resurrection.

912
01:18:19,153 --> 01:18:23,365
I haven't betrayed you,
but my help stops here.

913
01:18:23,532 --> 01:18:26,409
What the hell
are you talking about?

914
01:18:29,955 --> 01:18:32,040
Damn chicha.

915
01:18:32,208 --> 01:18:34,417
Is it money you're after?

916
01:18:34,585 --> 01:18:38,004
You can stick your dirty
money where it fits.

917
01:18:38,172 --> 01:18:41,007
You were better off
dead, Cassidy.

918
01:18:41,175 --> 01:18:43,343
And I hope you soon will be.

919
01:18:43,511 --> 01:18:45,637
I'll drink until I forget this,

920
01:18:45,805 --> 01:18:48,223
but for you

921
01:18:48,391 --> 01:18:52,936
all the liquor in this shitty world
wouldn't be enough.

922
01:18:53,104 --> 01:18:55,563
In my day

923
01:18:55,731 --> 01:18:57,732
the outlaws would have
robbed banks

924
01:18:57,900 --> 01:18:59,818
and the Union Pacific.

925
01:18:59,985 --> 01:19:03,571
They would never have stolen
from the mining families, no sir.

926
01:19:03,739 --> 01:19:07,283
Mining families?
You better get off the bottle, Mackinley.

927
01:19:07,451 --> 01:19:10,078
- You're losing your Irish mind.
- Go to hell.

928
01:19:10,246 --> 01:19:11,871
He never stole from
the mining families.

929
01:19:12,039 --> 01:19:15,458
It's Patiño...
the Suyana Mine.

930
01:19:15,626 --> 01:19:17,085
You believe that?

931
01:19:17,253 --> 01:19:21,005
He tricked you
into believing that?

932
01:19:21,173 --> 01:19:23,967
Jesus, I almost pity you.

933
01:19:24,135 --> 01:19:26,636
Your Spanish friend
didn't work for Patiño.

934
01:19:26,804 --> 01:19:30,056
He worked for the miners.
The mine is theirs.

935
01:19:30,224 --> 01:19:33,101
They took it from Patiño
two years ago.

936
01:19:33,269 --> 01:19:34,519
What rock were you
hiding under?

937
01:19:34,687 --> 01:19:37,063
The whole country
was talking about it.

938
01:19:38,691 --> 01:19:41,025
The miners rebelled
against the owners...

939
01:19:41,193 --> 01:19:43,445
overdue wages, murders...
the usual.

940
01:19:43,612 --> 01:19:47,615
There was a huge battle.
A lot of miners got killed.

941
01:19:47,783 --> 01:19:50,535
Then justice stepped in and...

942
01:19:50,703 --> 01:19:52,954
this country is
full of surprises...

943
01:19:53,122 --> 01:19:55,748
they decided in favor
of the miners.

944
01:19:55,916 --> 01:19:59,502
They awarded ownership of the mine
to the surviving families.

945
01:19:59,670 --> 01:20:01,546
This is no coincidence,
of course...

946
01:20:01,714 --> 01:20:04,507
the mine was almost empty.

947
01:20:04,675 --> 01:20:06,759
Even the Spanish engineer
who worked for Patiño

948
01:20:06,927 --> 01:20:08,636
stood up for them.

949
01:20:08,804 --> 01:20:12,348
Poor fools,
they trusted a Spaniard.

950
01:20:17,313 --> 01:20:20,315
There are times
when you'd prefer to be dead,

951
01:20:20,483 --> 01:20:24,194
don't you agree?

952
01:20:27,531 --> 01:20:30,658
Goodbye and good riddance,
Mr. Blackthorn.

953
01:21:25,506 --> 01:21:27,924
(children laughing)

954
01:21:35,266 --> 01:21:36,307
(speaking Spanish)
Here you go, sir.

955
01:21:41,564 --> 01:21:44,524
We'll catch him.
He can't be far away.

956
01:21:46,318 --> 01:21:48,736
Or what do you think, Mackinley?

957
01:21:51,365 --> 01:21:55,952
WANTED
$10,000 REWARD

958
01:21:58,747 --> 01:21:59,747
No.

959
01:22:00,916 --> 01:22:02,125
It's not him.

960
01:22:02,293 --> 01:22:04,502
It's not the one
who escaped from the clinic.

961
01:22:04,670 --> 01:22:06,296
Cassidy died years ago.

962
01:22:06,463 --> 01:22:10,049
Are you crazy, Mackinley?
You recognized him yourself!

963
01:22:10,217 --> 01:22:11,676
It wasn't him.

964
01:22:12,678 --> 01:22:14,178
Of course it's him!

965
01:22:14,346 --> 01:22:18,224
This is the man I left
in my clinic, with you.

966
01:22:18,392 --> 01:22:20,977
You're a fucking sentimentalist.

967
01:22:24,648 --> 01:22:26,316
Mackinley.

968
01:22:29,445 --> 01:22:32,488
We're going to see
if you're right or not.

969
01:22:33,574 --> 01:22:35,742
We leave at dawn.

970
01:22:35,909 --> 01:22:37,744
And you're coming with us.

971
01:23:34,134 --> 01:23:36,969
- (horse snorting)
- (hoofbeats)

972
01:24:43,662 --> 01:24:45,997
Okay, let's go, kid.

973
01:24:47,875 --> 01:24:50,668
(groaning)

974
01:24:52,963 --> 01:24:55,256
Butch: Shit.

975
01:24:59,011 --> 01:25:01,679
You'll get my suit dirty.

976
01:25:01,847 --> 01:25:04,015
It'll help keep you warm.

977
01:25:11,523 --> 01:25:13,941
Everybody will think we're dead

978
01:25:14,109 --> 01:25:16,110
and look at us...

979
01:25:16,278 --> 01:25:19,697
strong as trees,

980
01:25:19,865 --> 01:25:21,991
snow-covered trees.

981
01:25:24,536 --> 01:25:27,121
Bolivia.

982
01:25:29,041 --> 01:25:32,418
God damn it, Bolivia.

983
01:25:32,586 --> 01:25:36,547
Always knew
you'd be the last.

984
01:25:36,715 --> 01:25:39,801
Everybody's dead and you...

985
01:25:39,968 --> 01:25:42,720
you're all alone now

986
01:25:42,888 --> 01:25:46,474
so far from home,

987
01:25:46,642 --> 01:25:49,769
my poor friend.

988
01:25:53,482 --> 01:25:55,316
Okay.

989
01:25:55,484 --> 01:25:58,069
Do it.

990
01:26:02,574 --> 01:26:05,243
Now is a good time.

991
01:26:06,787 --> 01:26:08,412
Do it.

992
01:26:23,846 --> 01:26:25,847
(gunshot)

993
01:27:02,968 --> 01:27:05,928
James.

994
01:27:06,096 --> 01:27:07,972
Hey.

995
01:27:08,140 --> 01:27:10,141
Or should I say Butch?

996
01:27:10,309 --> 01:27:13,352
Mr. Butch Cassidy himself.

997
01:27:13,520 --> 01:27:15,855
(laughs)
I knew it.

998
01:27:16,023 --> 01:27:18,107
That explains
so many things.

999
01:27:18,275 --> 01:27:20,109
You know what?

1000
01:27:20,277 --> 01:27:23,154
In Tupiza
everyone was shouting

1001
01:27:23,322 --> 01:27:25,865
that the famous
gringo outlaw was alive.

1002
01:27:26,033 --> 01:27:28,409
And me buying new clothes...

1003
01:27:28,577 --> 01:27:30,870
can you imagine?

1004
01:27:32,623 --> 01:27:35,708
Take it easy.
They still must be far.

1005
01:27:44,593 --> 01:27:47,595
So here we are

1006
01:27:47,763 --> 01:27:50,139
just a few hours
from freedom

1007
01:27:50,307 --> 01:27:52,975
and the good life.

1008
01:27:53,143 --> 01:27:54,602
Are you okay?

1009
01:27:54,770 --> 01:27:57,772
You can't think
I abandoned you, right?

1010
01:27:57,940 --> 01:28:00,942
I just couldn't stay there
with so much going on.

1011
01:28:01,109 --> 01:28:03,653
And I knew you'd turn up.

1012
01:28:05,614 --> 01:28:09,033
That mine didn't belong
to Patiño?

1013
01:28:23,465 --> 01:28:27,009
And your name is not
James Blackthorn.

1014
01:28:27,177 --> 01:28:30,888
Well, we all have our secrets.

1015
01:28:31,056 --> 01:28:33,599
But now all the cards
are on the table.

1016
01:28:36,103 --> 01:28:38,813
No. You're right.
It wasn't his any longer.

1017
01:28:38,981 --> 01:28:41,273
So what?

1018
01:28:41,441 --> 01:28:45,778
It had different owners...
owners anyway.

1019
01:28:45,946 --> 01:28:48,572
$50,000, James.

1020
01:28:48,740 --> 01:28:52,159
That's no lie.
Come on, let's go.

1021
01:28:52,327 --> 01:28:54,704
Look, there are
your mountains.

1022
01:28:54,871 --> 01:28:57,623
We're almost there.
I'll be your gang now...

1023
01:28:57,791 --> 01:29:00,626
you and me, James.
You and me.

1024
01:29:00,794 --> 01:29:03,129
You said yourself...
you were dead,

1025
01:29:03,296 --> 01:29:05,381
breeding horses
in that old house.

1026
01:29:05,549 --> 01:29:08,300
Now you have money
and you have it all...

1027
01:29:08,468 --> 01:29:10,511
your name, your life.

1028
01:29:10,679 --> 01:29:13,764
You're a damn legend,
and here you are.

1029
01:29:13,932 --> 01:29:16,225
Here you are.

1030
01:29:17,686 --> 01:29:19,603
Here I am.

1031
01:29:19,771 --> 01:29:22,481
(screaming)

1032
01:29:28,739 --> 01:29:32,241
Have you gone crazy?!

1033
01:29:32,409 --> 01:29:33,909
Motherfucker!

1034
01:29:34,077 --> 01:29:36,328
They'll be here shortly.

1035
01:29:36,496 --> 01:29:38,539
This time they've got
the army with them.

1036
01:29:38,707 --> 01:29:39,874
But you shot me!

1037
01:29:40,876 --> 01:29:42,293
Son of a bitch!

1038
01:29:48,759 --> 01:29:50,718
Is it the money?

1039
01:29:50,886 --> 01:29:54,513
How can you, bastard?

1040
01:29:54,681 --> 01:29:56,849
You never did see
the difference, did you?

1041
01:30:01,563 --> 01:30:03,814
For the Indians?

1042
01:30:03,982 --> 01:30:06,650
For a bunch of miners?
For them?

1043
01:30:06,818 --> 01:30:08,903
And what about me?

1044
01:30:09,071 --> 01:30:11,030
I'm your friend.

1045
01:30:11,198 --> 01:30:14,700
I gave you everything...
everything.

1046
01:30:14,868 --> 01:30:16,827
I saved your life.

1047
01:30:16,995 --> 01:30:19,663
I gave you
your name back, I did.

1048
01:30:19,831 --> 01:30:23,334
Difference?
What's the fucking difference?

1049
01:30:23,502 --> 01:30:25,461
What's the fucking difference?

1050
01:30:39,768 --> 01:30:42,228
Are you going to leave me
like this,

1051
01:30:42,395 --> 01:30:44,814
you son of a bitch?

1052
01:30:44,981 --> 01:30:47,650
Are you?

1053
01:30:49,903 --> 01:30:53,989
Okay. Okay.

1054
01:30:54,157 --> 01:30:55,991
Give the money
back to them.

1055
01:30:56,159 --> 01:30:58,077
Give the money back
to them,

1056
01:30:58,245 --> 01:31:01,872
but don't leave me
here, please.

1057
01:31:03,875 --> 01:31:05,501
Please.

1058
